What you'll practice: Prefix Sums. It teaches you how to answer range sum queries in O(1) time after an O(N) preprocessing step, which is a great stepping stone before jumping into Segment Trees.

2. LeetCode 307: Range Sum Query - Mutable (Medium)
Why it's similar: This introduces the update aspect (like your Type 1 queries). You have to find the sum of a range, but the array elements can change between queries.
What you'll practice: Segment Trees or Fenwick Trees. This is the exact core data structure needed for the Infosys question, just without the added complexity of "lazy propagation" (since LeetCode 307 only does single-point updates, not range updates).
